{"key":"post-17177604","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17177604</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The longer you keep the bark intact(helps retain log moisture level) the longer the log will produce. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's not just about moisture, but fruiting surface.&amp;nbsp; The mushrooms form on the bark, not the bare wood.&amp;nbsp; Smack them with a rubber or rawhide mallet if necessary to protect the bark, or pour in some wax to seal the damage if the bark gets torn.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Concussion is a well known shiitake pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; Shiitake also fruit all summer, and many of my best strains such as S75 don't react to a cold shock at all, so I skip it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, shiitake will perform better on sawdust than on whole logs outdoors as well as indoors, so growers should take note.&amp;nbsp; Some of the sawdust blocks below are in their third and fourth years fruiting and only a fraction of original size.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-32/437029127-Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate3.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/12-32/437029127-thumb_Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate3.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/12-32/437029108-thumb_Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate2.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/12-32/437029090-Outdoor_shiitake_with_depleted_substrate.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_